Many-to-Many Relationship (JPA / Database)
1. Join Table Requirement

A separate join table must be created in the database.
This join table contains two foreign keys, each referencing one side of the relationship.


2. Owning vs Non-Owning Side

In JPA:

The side that defines the @JoinTable + @JoinColumn is the owning side.
The side that defines @ManyToMany(mappedBy = "...") is the non-owning (inverse) side.




3. Join Table Written on the Parent Side

The @JoinTable annotation is usually placed on the owning/parent side to define:

The join table name
The owning side's FK column
The inverse side's FK column




4. Database Updates

Only the owning side can perform updates to the relationship.

Adding / removing associations is controlled from the owner.
The non-owner cannot update the join table—only read it.




5. Object Reference Requirement

The owning side must contain a reference to the non-owning side's object.
This ensures:

JPA can manage the association correctly.
The join table is updated through the owning entity’s list/set.